          {
            "text": "Method",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Bake the sponge layers",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Preheat the oven to 180°C conventional. Grease and line two 20 cm round tins. Beat the butter and sugar until pale and fluffy. Beat in the eggs one at a time, then fold in the flour and lemon zest. Divide between the tins and bake for 25 to 30 minutes until golden and pulling away from the sides. While the cakes are still warm, brush the soaking syrup over both surfaces. Cool completely on racks.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Make the filling",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Whip the double cream with the 20 ml elderflower cordial to soft peaks. Place the first sponge on a serving plate and spread the lemon curd over the top to within 1 cm of the edge. Spoon the elderflower cream over the lemon curd and spread gently, then place the second sponge on top, pressing very lightly.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Make the icing and finish",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Mix the sifted icing sugar with the elderflower cordial and lemon juice to a pourable icing. It should be thin enough to flow but not transparent. Pour over the top of the assembled cake and allow it to drip naturally over the edges. Leave to set for 30 minutes before cutting.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
